quran[27]{c,v,t,f}:
95,1,"By the fig and the olive; {1}",footnotes:1:There has been much difference of opinion among the commentators about the explanation of this verse. Hasan Basri
95,2,"and by the Mount Sinai, {1}",footnotes:1:The words in the original are Tur-i-Sinin. Sinin is another name for the Sinai Peninsula. It is called Saina or Sina as well as Sinin. In the Quran itself at one place the words Tur-i-Sinin have been used. Since the land in which Mt. Sinai is located is well known as Sina
95,3,"and by this city (of Makkah), a haven of peace:"
95,4,"surely We created man in the best mould; {1}",footnotes:1:This is the truth for which the oath has been sworn by the lands of the fig and the olive (i.e. Syria and Palestine) and Mt. Sinai and Makkah
95,5,"then We reverted him to the lowest of the low, {1}",footnotes:1:The commentators in general have given two meanings of this:
95,6,"except those who have faith and do righteous deeds. Theirs is a never ending reward. {1}",footnotes:1:The commentators who have taken asfala-safilin to imply the state of extreme old age when man loses his sense and reason
95,7,"Who, then, can give the lie to you, (O Prophet), about the Reward and the Punishment? {1}",footnotes:1:Another translation of this verse can be: What can after this (O man) make you deny the judgment? In both cases the intention and purpose remains the same. That is when it is a common observation in human society that a section of mankind which has been created in the best of molds and nature
95,8,"Is not Allah the Greatest of all sovereigns? {1}",footnotes:1:That is
96,1,"Recite {1} in the name of your Lord {2} Who created, {3}",footnotes:1:As we have explained in the Introduction
96,2,"created man from a clot of congealed blood. {1}",footnotes:1:After making mention generally of the creation of the universe
96,3,"Recite: and your Lord is Most Generous,"
96,4,"Who taught by the pen, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
96,5,"taught man what he did not know. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
96,6,"Nay, {1} surely man transgresses;",footnotes:1:That is
96,7,"for he believes himself to be self-sufficient. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
96,8,"Surely to your Lord is your return. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
96,9,"Did you see him who forbids"
96,10,"a servant (of Allah) when he prays? {1}",footnotes:1:A servant: the Messenger (peace be upon him) of Allah himself. The Prophet (peace be upon him) has been mentioned by this epithet at several places in the Quran. For example
96,11,"Did you consider: what if he is on the Right Way,"
96,12,"and enjoins piety?"
96,13,"Did you consider: what if he gives the lie (to the Truth) and turns away (from it)?"
96,14,"Does he not know that Allah sees everything? {1}",footnotes:1:The audience here apparently is every just man
96,15,"No indeed; {1} if he does not desist, We shall drag him by the forelock;",footnotes:1:That is
96,16,"by the lying forelock steeped in sin. {1}",footnotes:1:The forelock here implies the person with the forelock.
96,17,"So let him summon his helpmates; {1}",footnotes:1:As we have explained in the Introduction
96,18,"We too shall summon the guards of Hell. {1}",footnotes:1:According to the explanation given by Qatadah
96,19,"No, not at all. Never obey him. But prostrate yourself and become nigh (to your Lord). {1}",footnotes:1:Sajdah (prostration) here implies the Prayer
